name: Harvest, use & livelihoods
note: Assessment of the extent of hunting and the capacity for this species to be used as a sustainable resource, even at the population level, would significantly facilitate alternative management regimes - especially in Central Africa.

name: Life history & ecology
note: Mecistops cataphractus is, along with Tomistoma, the least known of crocodilians in terms of basic ecology, and this lack of information is a barrier to the establishment of biologically sound management programmes. Studies of population dynamics, movement and habitat use should be prioritized in order to establish baseline data to guide the creation of protected areas and management plans for the species in the wild. Additionally, evaluation of habitat suitability with specific reference to freshwater fisheries will capitalize on the highly aquatic, and almost exclusively piscivorous, habits of M. cataphractus to facilitate its utility as an umbrella and flagship species around which protected areas can provide a haven from small-scale, local, subsistence fisheries and in turn increase the sustainability of the fishery resource for local fishing communities.

name: Population size, distribution & trends
note: While our level of knowledge of the distribution and status of M. cataphractus has increased considerably since 1998, there is still little known about the species status in the wild, and surveys are needed throughout the species range. Priority countries/areas include Liberia, Cote dIvoire (all protected areas), Ghana (Western Region), Nigeria (Cross and Niger River drainages), Gabon, Republic of Congo, Central African Republic (Sangha-Dja complex), and Democratic Republic of Congo. Surveys should be conducted in collaboration with relevant management authorities to promote capacity-building and development of management plans.

name: Taxonomy
note: Recent research has found significant evidence for genetic and morphological divergence at the species level between West and Central Africa (Shirley 2013, Shirley et al. In review).  The results support splitting this species into two.  Further research sampling populations from Togo to Cameroon will allow us to more precisely delimit each species distribution.

name: Population size, distribution & trends
note: Determine European Turtle-dove numbers in Important Bird and Biodiversity Areas (IBAs) and Key Biodiversity Areas (KBAs). name: Harvest, use & livelihoods
note: Conduct a socio-economic study on the reasons that people illegally kill European Turtle-doves. Identify reasons for wood harvesting in key areas of the wintering ground. If exported, identify where better regulation is required, if used for fuel, promote alternative fuels and cooking methods.

name: Threats
note:
Collect and analyse data on hunting tourism and illegal killing. Research the effects of disease and parasites on European Turtle-doves. Research the effects of pesticide and herbicide use on European Turtle-doves and the extent of their use within the wintering grounds.
Determine the impact of collisions with wind and electrical infrastructure on European Turtle-dove populations. Research the effects of predation of European Turtle-doves. Analyse evidence of competition of European Turtle-doves with other species.

name: Species Action/Recovery Plan

name: Other

Implement tracking studies and analyse new tracking, isotopic, ring-recovery data and wing collection samples of bagged birds to determine the origin and sub-species of killed birds. Evaluate small-scale projects that benefit the European Turtle-dove. Assess the goals of NGOs working in European Turtle-dove wintering sites and identify where goals overlap to promote these goals.
